   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1838-10_page01.jpg"/>
            <p>
               <add>his thefts were</add>
               <del>thefts were</del> premeditated &amp; systematic - In short
               <del>occurrences <unclear>but that</unclear>
               </del> he was habitually
               &amp; without <add>shame</add>
               <del/>, yet not without fear
               an intellectual pilferer &amp; plunderer
               Both or either as occasion prompted &amp;
               circumstances required - With the
               timid he was bold, with the bold he
               was timid - Persons without a name
               <del/> or with names unknown
               in the world he treated absolutely as
               barbarians, who did not know the
               value of their <add>own</add> gold and <del>might have</del>
               <add>if they chanced to possess</add>
               earrings, &amp; nose jewels, frightful things! They
               might <add>be</add> plucked from them without remorse
               &amp; converted to better use <del>
                  <unclear/>
               </del> by
               any civilised <unclear/>
               <note place="left">
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">EDGEWORTH, M</persName>
               L.300</note>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1838-10_page02.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
